2025-08-22 14:55:20,073 - root - Response: **Impact of tire‑pressure on the distance travelled per rotation (idealised, no‑slip, fixed‑tread‑length)**  

In an idealised steady‑state situation the distance covered in one full revolution is simply the circumference of the outermost surface that actually contacts the ground.  For a rim of radius \(R_{0}\) and a tire whose tread length \(L_{t}\) is fixed by the steel belt, the radius of the outermost tread surface, \(R_{\text{eff}}\), is

\[
R_{\text{eff}} = R_{0} + \Delta r(P,\;F),
\]

where \(\Delta r\) is the radial deflection of the tire under the vehicle load \(F\).  
Because the tread arc length is constant, any reduction of the contact patch (a shorter chord) must be accommodated by a change in the shape of the tire cross‑section: the tire flattens less, so the outer radius increases.  The distance per rotation is therefore

\[
s = 2\pi R_{\text{eff}} = 2\pi\!\left(R_{0}+\Delta r\right).
\]

---

### How pressure enters the picture

The radial deflection can be approximated by a linear elastic model in which the tire behaves as a “spring” in the radial direction:

\[
\Delta r \approx \frac{F}{k_{\text{rad}}(P)} .
\]

The radial stiffness \(k_{\text{rad}}\) grows with internal pressure because the tire’s sidewalls are pre‑stressed and the contact patch area shrinks.  A simple first‑order estimate is

\[
k_{\text{rad}}(P) \;\approx\; \frac{P\,A_{\text{c}}}{\delta},
\]

where \(A_{\text{c}}\) is the contact‑patch area (≈ \(F/P\)) and \(\delta\) is the characteristic deflection of the sidewall.  Substituting gives

\[
\Delta r \;\approx\; \frac{F\,\delta}{P\,A_{\text{c}}} \;\approx\; \frac{\delta}{P},
\]

so the radial deflection decreases inversely with pressure.  Consequently

\[
R_{\text{eff}}(P) \;\approx\; R_{0} + \frac{\delta}{P},
\qquad
s(P) \;\approx\; 2\pi\!\left(R_{0}+\frac{\delta}{P}\right).
\]

Thus, in this idealised framework, **increasing tire pressure reduces the radial flattening, increases the effective radius, and therefore increases the distance travelled per rotation**.  Conversely, a lower pressure flattens the tire more, decreases the effective radius, and reduces the distance per revolution.

---

### Practical implication for the idealised model

Because the tread length is fixed, the change in effective radius comes entirely from the redistribution of the contact‑patch geometry.  The vehicle’s speed‑encoder (e.g., a wheel‑speed sensor) will register a higher tick rate for a given ground speed when the tire is inflated to a higher pressure, purely because each wheel rotation now covers a longer arc length.  This theoretical result holds regardless of the specific material or construction details, as long as the assumptions of no slippage, rigid tread length, and elastic radial behaviour are respected.
