2025-08-22 14:58:21,301 - root - Response: **Thermodynamic‑Ideal‑Gas View of Tire‑Pressure Effects**

In the idealised picture the tire is a rigid torus whose cross‑section is a steel‑belted tread of fixed arc length \(L_t\).  The only variable that can change the distance travelled per rotation is the effective outer radius \(R_{\text{out}}\) of the torus.  Because the belt keeps the tread perimeter constant, any change in the internal gas pressure \(P\) must be accommodated by a change in the cross‑sectional area \(A\) of the tire.  For a fixed amount of air \(n\) and at constant temperature \(T\) the ideal‑gas law gives

\[
P\,V = nRT \;\;\Rightarrow\;\; V=\frac{nRT}{P}\;,
\]

and the volume of the torus is \(V = A\,(2\pi R_0)\) where \(R_0\) is the rim radius.  Thus

\[
A(P)=\frac{nRT}{2\pi R_0\,P}\, .
\]

For a circular cross‑section the area is \(A=\pi r_c^2\), so the characteristic cross‑sectional radius scales as

\[
r_c(P)=\sqrt{\frac{nRT}{2\pi^2 R_0\,P}}\; .
\]

The outer radius of the tire is \(R_{\text{out}}=R_0+r_c\).  Consequently the distance travelled per full rotation is

\[
L(P)=2\pi R_{\text{out}}=2\pi\left(R_0+\sqrt{\frac{nRT}{2\pi^2 R_0\,P}}\right)\; .
\]

Hence, in this idealised model, the distance per rotation decreases as the internal pressure increases because the cross‑sectional radius shrinks (\(r_c\propto P^{-1/2}\)).  Temperature variations would modify the prefactor \(nRT\); for isothermal conditions the \(P^{-1/2}\) dependence remains.  Thus, ignoring slippage and tread deformation, a higher tire pressure leads to a slightly shorter effective radius and therefore a reduced distance per rotation, all else being equal.
