\[
s(P)=\int_{0}^{2\pi}\!r(\theta;P)\,d\theta ,
\]

where the dependence on pressure \(P\) enters through the deformation of the cross‑section.  For a perfectly circular outer surface (the usual approximation in a first‑order model) we have \(r(\theta;P)=R_{\text{eff}}(P)\) and therefore

\[
s(P)=2\pi R_{\text{eff}}(P).
\]

The effective radius is the rim radius plus the tread thickness \(t\) minus the reduction caused by the flattening of the contact patch.  If the load on the tire is \(W\) and the tread width is \(w\), the contact‑patch area is \(A=W/P\) and the patch length along the wheel is \(l=A/w\).  Geometrically the flattening reduces the outer radius by

\[
\Delta R(P)\;\approx\;\frac{l^{2}}{8R_{0}}
          \;=\;\frac{1}{8R_{0}}\left(\frac{W}{P\,w}\right)^{2},
\]

so that

\[
R_{\text{eff}}(P)=R_{0}+t-\Delta R(P).
\]

Consequently

\[
\boxed{\,s(P)=2\pi\Bigl(R_{0}+t-\frac{1}{8R_{0}}\Bigl(\frac{W}{P\,w}\Bigr)^{2}\Bigr)\,}.
\]

**Interpretation**

Higher pressure \(P\) shortens the contact‑patch length \(l\) and therefore diminishes the flattening \(\Delta R\).  The wheel’s outer radius moves closer to the rim radius plus tread thickness, reducing the circumference and thus the distance travelled per rotation.  In the limit of very high pressure the flattening vanishes, \(R_{\text{eff}}\to R_{0}+t\), and the wheel behaves as a rigid circle.  Conversely, at low pressure the patch length grows, the effective radius shrinks, and each revolution covers a slightly shorter distance.  The effect is quadratic in \(1/P\) and is typically very small for realistic tire loads, but it is a purely geometric consequence of the fixed‑tread‑length assumption in an idealised, no‑slip model.
