2025-08-22 15:08:34,008 - root - Response: **Distance per rotation – idealised, no‑slip, fixed‑tread length**

In the idealised picture the only quantity that can change the linear distance covered in one full revolution is the *effective* outer radius of the wheel, \(R_{\text{eff}}\).  The distance per rotation is simply the circumference of the outermost surface that touches the ground,

\[
s(p)=2\pi R_{\text{eff}}(p)\, .
\]

Because the tread is steel‑belted, its arc length \(L_t\) measured along the rim–to–ground line is constant.  Let the rim radius be \(R_0\) and let the tread cross‑section be approximated by a circular arc of radius \(r_t\).  The angular extent of the tread, \(\phi\), is the angle subtended by the tread arc at the centre of the wheel.  By definition

\[
L_t=(R_0+r_t)\,\phi \qquad\Longrightarrow\qquad R_{\text{eff}}=R_0+r_t=\frac{L_t}{\phi}\, .
\]

When the tire pressure is raised the sidewalls flatten, the tread spreads laterally, and the contact patch lengthens; consequently \(\phi\) increases.  Since \(L_t\) is fixed, the ratio \(L_t/\phi\) – and therefore \(R_{\text{eff}}\) – decreases.  Thus

\[
s(p)=\frac{2\pi L_t}{\phi(p)} ,
\]

with \(\phi(p)\) a monotonically increasing function of pressure.  To first order one may write

\[
\phi(p)\approx \phi_0+\alpha\,(p-p_0)\quad\Rightarrow\quad
s(p)\approx \frac{2\pi L_t}{\phi_0}\left[1-\frac{\alpha}{\phi_0}(p-p_0)\right] ,
\]

so the distance per rotation falls linearly with increasing pressure.

**Bottom line**  
In an idealised, no‑slip, fixed‑tread‑length wheel the distance travelled per rotation is \(s=2\pi R_{\text{eff}}\), where \(R_{\text{eff}}\) is the radius of the outermost tread point.  Raising the tire pressure flattens the sidewalls, increases the tread’s angular span \(\phi\), and therefore reduces \(R_{\text{eff}}\) and the distance per rotation.  The effect is a monotonic decrease of \(s\) with pressure, approximately linear for small pressure changes.
