Any change in internal air pressure merely alters the shape of the side‑wall (compressing or bulging it), but the belt itself cannot stretch or contract.  The contact patch moves along the rim, and the wheel’s outer contour may deform, yet the belt’s length—and hence the circumference that contacts the ground—remains unchanged.  Consequently, the distance travelled per rotation is **independent of tire pressure** in this idealised model.

Because the linear speed \(v\) of the vehicle is related to the angular velocity \(\omega\) by \(v = \omega\,s_{\text{rot}}\), the angular velocity itself is unaffected by pressure changes (assuming a fixed drive torque).  Therefore, in the absence of slippage and with a rigid rim and fixed‑length tread, a pressure variation has no theoretical impact on the distance per rotation or on the vehicle’s linear speed for a given wheel‑spin rate.
