Let the rim be a circle of radius \(R_{0}\) and let the steel‑belted tread be a closed, smooth curve \(\gamma(\theta)\) in the wheel‑cross‑section plane, parametrised by the polar angle \(\theta\in[0,2\pi]\) measured from the vertical line through the centre of the wheel.  The radial coordinate of the outer surface is \(r(\theta)=R_{0}+u(\theta)\), where \(u(\theta)\) is the radial deflection of the rubber envelope (positive outward).  Because the belt is inextensible, the arc length of the belt portion of \(\gamma\) is a fixed constant \(L_{t}\); in the idealised model this constraint is written  
\[
\int_{0}^{2\pi}\sqrt{\,r(\theta)^{2}+r'(\theta)^{2}\,}\;d\theta=L_{t}\,.
\]
The distance travelled in one full revolution is simply the length of the curve traced by a point on the outer rim, i.e.  
\[
s=\int_{0}^{2\pi} r(\theta)\,d\theta\;=\;2\pi R_{\text{eff}},\qquad 
R_{\text{eff}}=\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{0}^{2\pi} r(\theta)\,d\theta .
\]

A change in internal pressure \(p\) modifies the normal stress field in the rubber, causing the envelope to bulge outward.  In a linearised elastostatic setting one may write
\[
\delta u(\theta)=\alpha(\theta)\,\Delta p,
\]
where \(\alpha(\theta)\) is the local compliance of the rubber (a function of the material properties, wall thickness, and the geometry of the cross‑section).  Substituting \(r(\theta)=R_{0}+u(\theta)\) into the arc‑length constraint and differentiating with respect to \(p\) yields a relation between \(\delta u(\theta)\) and \(\Delta p\) that preserves \(L_{t}\).  The resulting change in distance per rotation is then
\[
\delta s=\int_{0}^{2\pi}\delta u(\theta)\,d\theta
      =\Delta p\int_{0}^{2\pi}\alpha(\theta)\,d\theta .
\]
Thus, in the idealised no‑slip, fixed‑tread‑length model, the impact of a pressure change on the distance travelled per rotation is governed entirely by the *effective outer radius* \(R_{\text{eff}}\); it is the integral of the radial deflection over the wheel’s angular coordinate.  Any change in pressure that preserves the belt arc length merely redistributes the radial deflection, and the net change in travel distance is the average of that redistribution multiplied by \(2\pi\).
